"24N":{"department":"CHEM","number":"24N","title":"Nutrition and History","description":"Preference to freshmen. Intended to broaden the introductory chemistry experience.  Fundamentals of human nutrition with emphasis on the chemistry and biochemistry of the known macro- and micronutrients (carbohydrate, protein, lipid, vitamins, minerals).  Historical context in which food sources are discovered and developed, and sociological and economic effects of those events on human populations. Prerequisite: high school chemistry. Recommended: 31A,B, or 31X, or 33.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":112240,"primary":[[],[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"2:15:00 PM","end":"4:05:00 PM","location":""}],"id":10186}]],"primary_type":"Introsem"},
"251":{"department":"CHEM","number":"251","title":"Advanced Inorganic Chemistry","description":"Primarily intended for first-year graduate students, as a review of some of the basic concepts in inorganic chemistry. Specific topics covered will include: symmetry, group theory, electronic structure of molecules and solids, and reactivity of coordination complexes. Prerequisite: Advanced undergraduate-level inorganic chemistry","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":112312,"primary":[[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,true],"start":"1:15:00 PM","end":"2:30:00 PM","location":"Braunlec"}],"id":26750}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"253":{"department":"CHEM","number":"253","title":"Advanced Inorganic Chemistry","description":"Electronic structure and physical properties of transition metal complexes. Ligand field and molecular orbital theories, magnetism and magnetic susceptibility, electron paramagnetic resonance including hyperfine interactions and zero field splitting and electronic absorption spectroscopy including vibrational interactions. Prerequisite: 153 or the equivalent.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":112313,},
"255":{"department":"CHEM","number":"255","title":"Advanced Inorganic Chemistry (CHEM 155)","description":"Chemical reactions of organotransition metal complexes and their role in homogeneous catalysis. Analogous patterns among reactions of transition metal complexes in lower oxidation states. Physical methods of structure determination. Prerequisite: one year of physical chemistry.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":112314,"primary":[[],[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"11:00:00 AM","end":"12:15:00 PM","location":"Chemistry Gazebo"}],"id":18102}]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"258A":{"department":"CHEM","number":"258A","title":"Research Progress in Inorganic Chemistry","description":"Required of all second-, third-, and fourth-year Ph.D. candidates in inorganic chemistry. Students present their research progress in written and oral forms (A); present a seminar in the literature of the field of research (B); and formulate, write, and orally defend a research proposal (C). Second-year students register for A; third-year students register for B; fourth-year students register for C.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":200173,},
